# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: guerrier-courses
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] Kots was born in Borisoglebsk, Tambov to Berlin-born linguist and botanist Alfred Kots and Evgenia (Johanna) Alexandrovna née Grassman.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] He began to collect natural history specimens at a young age and was educated at the Moscow classical gymnasium.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] He learned to stuff and prepare animal specimens from F.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] Yuri Felman and received a gold medal for his taxidermy in 1896.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] Lorenz and Mikhail Menzbier he went on a scientific expedition to Western Siberia in 1899 and collected a large number of specimens for which he received a silver medal from the Russian Society for Acclimatization of Animals and Plants.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] He joined Moscow University in 1901 and between his studies he made a trip to European museum and graduated in 1906.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] In 1907 he began to teach evolution to women at Moscow university at the invitation of Petr Sushkin and Nikolai Koltsov.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] Lorenz were passed on to him and he then began to establish a small museum which became the Darwin Museum in 1922.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] He married Nadezhda Nikolayevna Ladygina, one of his students, in 1911 and they had a son who they named as Rudolf after Rudolf Steiner who greatly influenced them.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] Kots taught at the Moscow University, the Military Pedagogical Academy, gave numerous popular lectures, was a director of Moscow Zoo, and the Darwin Museum.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-kots] After his death there was a plan to dissolve the museum but it was saved by V.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-stoletov] Alexander Stoletov defended his doctoral dissertation in 1872 and became professor at Moscow University a year later.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-stoletov] After defending his dissertation he became a renowned scientist worldwide.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-stoletov] He attended the opening ceremony of the physical laboratory in Cambridge in 1874, and represented Russia at the first World Congress of Electricity in Paris in 1881, where he presented his work on links between electrostatic and electromagnetic values.
[src:guerrier-courses/aleksandr-stoletov] His major contributions include pioneer work in the field of ferromagnetism and discovery of the laws and principles of the outer photoelectric effect.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] Petersburg where his father was an artistic portrait photographer while his mother was a musician.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] An interest in music among the children made him interested in acoustics.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] While at high school he became a friend of P.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] Lebedev and graduated from Moscow University in physics and mathematics.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] He then joined the St Petersburg Railway Institute and studied engineering after which he went to the University of Strasbourg where he focused on experimental physics under K.F.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] Braun and on theoretical physics under Emil Cohn.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] His doctorate in 1897 was on the absorption of electrical waves by electrolytes.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] He worked at the Moscow Engineering College from 1897 where his work included a demonstration of the magnetic field created by moving electrical charges.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] He constructed a simple magnetometer in 1903.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] He became director of the Railway Engineers Institute from 1905 and also taught at the Moscow University from 1906.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] After the death of Lebedev he presided over the Moscow Physics Society and from 1917 he was involved in organizing higher education in physics.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] Diagnosed with cancer he moved to Milan and wrote a textbook on electricity that went through multiple editions.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-eichenwald] In 1903 he demonstrated that static charges on a disc that was rotated could generate a magnetic field.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] Chuprov's father was an Orthodox priest based in Mosalsk.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] Alexander attended the Law Department of the Moscow University where he became interested in Wilhelm Roscher's research.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] He founded the Moscow Society to Disseminate Technical Knowledge in 1869 and was elected into the Russian Academy of Sciences in 1887.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] Chuprov has been described as the founder of transport economics and the multiple-factor analysis of economic regions.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] In his landmark work *The Railway Economy* (1875–78) he analyzed statistics on railway traffic.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] He distinguished one region from another according to "the value of the market, the cost of transportation, and demographic indicators".
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] Chuprov became known as "the heart and soul" of zemstvo statistical investigations and sample surveys in the Russian Empire.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] His researchers are said to have interviewed 4.5 million Russian muzhiks.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] Their mission was to provide a modern statistical description of the Russian peasant commune, or obschina.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] Chuprov viewed the Russian obshchina as a valuable social institution which should be preserved.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] Chuprov was a lifelong friend of another prominent statistician, Ivan Yanzhul.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] One of his students at the Moscow University was Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-ivanovich-chuprov] Chuprov (1874–1926) is said to have given "much impetus to statistics in pre-revolutionary Russia".
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-manuilov] He was the Minister of Education in the first Provisional Government and from 1924 was in the central administration of Gosbank, the Soviet state bank.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] A general's son, Veselovsky studied privately with Fyodor Buslaev and attended the Moscow University from 1854 to 1858.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] After a brief stint in Spain as a tutor to the Russian ambassador's son, Veselovsky continued his education with Heymann Steinthal in Berlin and Prague and spent three years working in the libraries of Italy.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] Upon his return to Russia, he delivered lectures in Moscow and St.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] Petersburg and was elected a Member of the St.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] Veselovsky's early studies of medieval Italian literature led him to believe that many plots and literary devices were imported to Europe from the Orient through Byzantium.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] Looking at literature primarily from a genetic point of view, Alexander Veselovsky and his brother Aleksey (1843-1918) attempted to construct a comprehensive theory of the origin and development of poetry.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] In 1899, Veselovsky famously argued that "the font and syncretic root of poetic genres" may be traced to ritualized popular games and folk incantations.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] In the Soviet Union, Veselovsky and his followers were criticized for their "ethnographism", which allowed "source study to grow to a hypertrophied degree, thus dissolving the specific character of the literary work into a collection of *influences*".
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] On 14 August 1946 the Central Committee of the Communist Party adopted a resolution specifically condemning "kowtowing" to the bourgeois West by the so-called Veselovskyists.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexander-veselovsky] The Russian Formalists largely shared a critical view of Veselovsky's theory, although it has been suggested that Veselovsky's doctrine was actually a point from which they evolved "in a linear, if polemical, way".
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] Glagoleva was born in 1884 in what was then the Russian Empire, and educated in a secondary school in Tula, an industrial city south of Moscow.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] She worked as a schoolteacher in the country from 1900 to 1906, then studied physics and mathematics with Alexander Alexandrowitsch Eichenwald and Nikolay Umov in the Moscow Higher Courses for Women.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] After finishing her studies there in 1910, she became an assistant for the Higher Courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] She also continued to work at the Second Moscow State University when it was established as a continuation of the Higher Courses in 1918, during the Russian Revolution.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] At Moscow State University, she became the founding head of a department of applied physics for the natural sciences in 1932.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] She became a full member of the Research Institute of Physics of Moscow State University in 1933, and was awarded a doctorate (on the basis of past work, with no thesis) in 1935.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] She also headed of department at the Medical Institute of the Second University.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] She retired from this position for medical reasons in 1937, and from her teaching and administrative responsibilities at Moscow State University in 1939.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] In the early 1920s she began her work on the generation of microwaves by passing sparks through metal filings, embedded in oil.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] This led her in the mid-1920s to place the entire electromagnetic spectrum into a single continuum, and by the late 1920s she was studying the spectral power density of the resulting radiation.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] This research developed in the 1930s into her studies of the far infrared spectrum, using diffraction gratings to isolate emissions of different frequencies.
[src:guerrier-courses/alexandra-glagoleva-arkadieva] Her final research topic, in the late 1930s and early 1940s, considered the detailed emission mechanism and modes of vibration of the microwave emitter that she had invented in her earlier work.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The **Higher Courses for Women** in Moscow (Russian: Московские высшие женские курсы, romanized: *Moskovskiye Vysshiye Zhenskiye Kursy*, lit.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] 'Moscow Higher Women's Courses') was a university for women between 1872 and 1918 (with a break in 1888–1900), after which they were transformed into the 2nd Moscow State University.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] It was one of the largest and most prominent women's higher education institutions in the Russian Empire, second only to the Bestuzhev Courses in Saint Petersburg.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] It was founded and administered by Vladimir I.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] At the beginning of 1871, the supernumerary professor of general history of Moscow University, V.I.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Guerrier, sent a note to the trustee of the Moscow educational district, Prince A.P.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Shirinsky-Shikhmatov, about the advisability of opening higher women's courses in Moscow, to which he added the draft "Regulations on Higher Women's Courses", in which he outlined the purpose and program of the created courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Guerrier persuaded the Minister of Public Education Count Dmitry A.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Tolstoy to sanction a higher school for women in Moscow.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In May 1872, the Minister of Public Education, Count D.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Tolstoy, agreed to the opening of higher women's courses in Moscow as a private educational institution and approved the "Regulations on Higher Women's Courses".
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] On November 1, 1872, at Volkhonka 16, in the building of the First Men's Gymnasium, the grand opening of the Moscow Higher Women's Courses (courses of Professor V.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Guerrier) took place, where professors of the Imperial Moscow University, priest A.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The course budget consisted of tuition fees and voluntary donations.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The first donations came from Guerrier's wife Evdokia Ivanovna, her aunt E.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] 13% of the sources of income for the courses were dividends from bonds purchased by Guerrier with a portion of the income from the activities of the courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In addition, additionally (1%) the course participants collected money to purchase books for the course library.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] To replenish the course budget, Guerrier staged charity performances at the Solodovnikov Theatre.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] For income from performances in 1883, 46 listeners were given allowances.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In addition, funds were sought through the sale of books and postcards printed in their own printing house.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Initially, training was designed for 2 years, and since 1879, according to the new Charter, 3 years.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The Moscow courses had a historical and philological orientation, the compulsory subjects were approved: the history of Russia and general history, Russian literature and general literature, the history of civilization and the history of art, physics.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] For those who wished, it was supposed to teach foreign languages, mathematics and hygiene.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Classes were paid: 30 rubles a year were paid for the entire course of a student, and 10 rubles a year for a separate subject–volunteers.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1875, the fee was 50 rubles a year; then – 100 rubles a year.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In the total volume of incoming financial resources, tuition fees amounted to more than 75%; part of the funds (up to 7%) were voluntary donations; from 1875 to 1882 Moscow Merchant Administration allocated 500 rubles a year for 10 scholarships.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1872–1873, the courses were located on Volkhonka in downtown Moscow, in 1873–1876 – in the premises of the Museum of Applied Knowledge on Prechistenka 32, and in 1877–1888 – in a building specially built for the Polytechnic Museum.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Regular students had to provide a certificate of secondary education upon entry or pass entrance exams in Russian and general history, Russian and general literature.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The listeners also submitted an autobiography, a certificate of moral conduct and political integrity from the governor general, two photographs and, without fail, permission from the eldest man in the family or spouse.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1881, a new humanitarian discipline was introduced in the courses – the history of philosophy.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Lectures at the courses were given by well-known professors of Moscow University (it was specifically stipulated in the Charter that mainly university professors would be invited as teachers).
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Among the first teachers were: Professor Fyodor A.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Bredikhin (physics, astronomy), Professor Alexander N.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Veselovsky (Russian literature), Professor Pavel G.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Vinogradov (History of the Middle Ages), Professor Vasily O.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Klyuchevsky (Russian history), Rector of Moscow University, Professor Vladimir S.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Lopatin (history of philosophy), Vladimir I.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Guerrier (history), Professor Nikolay I.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Storozhenko (general literature), Professor N.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Tikhonravov (ancient Russian literature), Fyodor I.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Since 1877, the history of the Russian language and ancient Russian literature was taught by V.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Chuprov (political economy), Aleksandr G.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Shakhov (history of foreign literature).
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The work of the courses was supervised by the Pedagogical Council, headed by Professor Sergey M.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The trustee committee of the courses included E.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] For 16 years, the courses issued 41 diplomas, which gave the right to teach in the senior classes of women's gymnasiums, in addition, 322 students passed the final exams, which gave them the right to teach in the junior classes of gymnasiums.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1886, the Ministry of Public Education, represented by Minister I.D.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Delyanov, forbade admission to all higher women's courses, motivating this measure by the need to develop new curricula and transfer courses to state support and in 1888 they have been closed.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Like its Saint Petersburg counterpart, the Guerrier Courses was established to prevent Russian women from studying abroad, which they had done since the universities were closed to women in Russia in 1863.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The courses provided university level education, but in contrast to the courses for men, they were not allowed to issue any formal degree, nor were they given government funding.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] They were closed in 1888 but opened again in 1900.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1900, graduates of secondary educational institutions from 41 provinces entered the courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The new courses were no longer a private institution, receiving part of the funds from the Ministry of Public Education.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The term of study in courses in 1900 increased to four years.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The newly opened courses had two departments – historical-philosophical and physical-mathematical.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1906, according to the new Charter, the faculty structure of the Courses was established.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In addition to the two existing ones, a Medical Faculty was opened (now the Russian National Research Medical University named after N.I.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Pirogov ), which made the structure of the courses close to the structure of a classical university (before the revolution, universities in Russia, as a rule, consisted of four faculties: historical – philological, physical and mathematical, medical and legal).
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Since 1911, the Bakhrushinskaya Hospital has become the clinical base of the Medical Faculty.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In the 1906–1907 academic year, the subject cycle system of teaching was introduced in the courses instead of the course system with specialization in the senior year.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] New curricula were also approved at all faculties.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] 15 hours a week were allotted for the study of compulsory subjects.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Guerrier was again the director of the courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] However, due to the fact that Vernadsky was simultaneously elected assistant rector of the Imperial Moscow University, he never took up his duties in the Courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Chaplygin was elected director of courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The courses were taught by such outstanding scientists as Vladimir I.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] One of the first women professors was Olga N.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Tsuberbiller, a graduate of courses, the author of the textbook on Analytic Geometry, "Problems and Exercises in Analytic Geometry", which was reprinted many times.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Vinogradov began to read a course in the history of pedagogical teachings .
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1905, the Moscow City Council decided to provide courses free of charge with a land plot on Devichye Pole .
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] On June 3, 1907, the laying of educational buildings took place (architect S.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Solovyov ) on a land plot along Malaya Tsaritsynskaya Street (now Malaya Pirogovskaya street).
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1908, the buildings of the Faculty of Physics and Chemistry ( now part of Moscow State University of Fine Chemical Technologies) and the Anatomical Theater (architect A.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] 1911 became a milestone in the life of the Moscow Higher Women's Courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In connection with the outbreak of a conflict between the Imperial Moscow University and the Minister of Public Education Lev A.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Kasso (named Kasso Case ), a large group of professors and teachers left the university, most of whom began to work at the Courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] By 1912, 227 professors, teachers, lecturers and assistants were involved in the courses, more than a third of whom had doctoral or master's degrees; among them: former rector of Moscow University Alexander A.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Khvostov, biologist Lev A.Tarassevitch, historian of philosophy Alexander V.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] There were also women among the staff of the courses: Maria Egorovna Becker, assistant to the course inspector; Olga Aleksandrovna Alferova, librarian; Nina Evgenievna Vedeneeva, assistant of the Department of Inorganic Chemistry (1914) and the Department of Physics (1916).
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1911, women were finally accepted at the Russian universities.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1912, Courses graduates for the first time received the right to take exams at the Imperial Moscow University.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] On November 17, 1912, the Council of Courses approved the “Regulations on leaving students at the Moscow Higher Women's Courses”, which allows leaving graduates at the faculty to prepare them for teaching on the proposal of a professor (professors) for 2 years.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Kots ' zoological collection was acquired for Courses, which laid the foundation for the Darwin Museum.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In the 1915–1916 academic year, the Moscow Higher Women's Courses were granted the right to conduct final exams and issue diplomas of higher education.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] By 1918, the courses numbered 8.3 thousand students, second only to Moscow State University .
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] On the initiative of former students, the "Society for the Delivery of Funds to Moscow Higher Women's Courses" was established.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] During 1900–1913 the number of female students increased from 223 to 7155.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] However, the annual graduation was no more than 30% of the number of applicants, which was due to the inability of the students to withstand heavy teaching loads and most of the time to study on their own.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Courses became one of the largest universities in the Russian Empire.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1882–1885, Maria Pavlovna Chekhova studied at the courses, after which she taught history and geography for 18 years at the private Moscow women's gymnasium L.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] The graduates of the Higher Women's Courses of this period were: Zinaida Ivanova (Zinaida Mirovich) and Ekaterina Kletnova.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] At different times, the courses were attended by: Vera Muromtseva, the future wife of Ivan A.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Bunin, translator, publicist; a close friend of Anton P.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Chekhov, Lidia Mizinova, an actress, translator, memoirist, literary and theater critic, who became the prototype of Nina Zarechnaya in the play "The Seagull "; Nadezhda Afanasyevna Bulgakova, sister of Mikhail A.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Vera Stepanovna Nechayeva became a well-known researcher of the work of Fyodor M.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Dostoevsky, the author of the most complete scientific biography of Vissarion G.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1910, Nadezhda Nikolaevna Sushkina (1889–1975), a soil scientist and microbiologist, graduated from the natural department and was the first to assess the influence of microorganisms on the composition of natural formations.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1907–1914, Bella Rosenfeld, the first wife of Marc Chagall, studied at the courses.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] In 1917, Lidia Karlovna Lepin (1891-1985), a specialist in physical and colloidal chemistry, a future academician of the Academy of Sciences of the Latvian SSR, graduated from the course.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Vera Varsanofieva was the first woman to be awarded the degree of Doctor of Geological and Mineralogical Sciences, geologist, geomorphologist, a member-correspondent of the USSR Academy of Pedagogical Sciences, and an honored scientist of the RSFSR.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Eugenia Gertsyk noted Russian translator and literary figure from the Silver Age.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Alexandra Glagoleva-Arkadieva the first Russian woman and physicist to become internationally known for her physics research on medical imaging using X-rays, mechanisms for generating microwaves, and spectrometry in the far infrared regions of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Srbui Lisitsian was an Armenian-Soviet ethnographer known for her development of a novel mathematical method for describing folk dance precisely using film techniques.
[src:guerrier-courses/guerrier-courses] Olga Tsuberbiller was a Russian mathematician noted for her creation of the textbook *Problems and Exercises in Analytic Geometry* was designated as an Honored Scientist of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic in 1955.
